st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women artists]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:American contraltos]]\n[[Category:American disco singers]]\n[[Category:American female pop singers]]\n[[Category:American female rock singers]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American performance artists]]\n[[Category:American pop guitarists]]\n[[Category:American pop rock singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings artists]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from California]]\n[[Category:Island Records artists]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for International Album of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Santa Barbara, California]]\n[[Category:Singers from California]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from California]]\n[[Category:UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors]]\n[[Category:American women in electronic music]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n", "name_user": "Vistadan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Remove double line", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Katy_Perry"}
{"title_page": "Associated petroleum gas", "text_new": "'''Associated petroleum gas''' (APG), or '''associated gas''', is a form of [[natural gas]] which is found with deposits of [[petroleum]], either dissolved in the oil or as a free \"gas cap\" above the oil in the reservoir.<ref>{{cite report |first=Tonje Hulbak |last=R\u00f8land |date=2010 |url=http://www.fni.no/doc&pdf/FNI-R1310.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720032900/http://www.fni.no/doc%26pdf/FNI-R1310.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-20 |title=Associated Petroleum Gas in Russia: Reasons for Non-utilization |work=FNI Report 13/2010 |location=Lysaker |publisher=Fridtjof Nansen Institute |page=53 |access-date=2018-10-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| publisher=The Society of Petroleum Engineers |date=2005 |url=http://www.spe.org/industry/docs/GlossaryPetroleumReserves-ResourcesDefinitions_2005.pdf |title=Glossary of terms used in Petroleum Reserves/Resources Definitions |accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref>  The gas can be utilized in a number of ways after processing: sold and included in the natural-gas distribution networks, used for on-site electricity generation with [[gas engine|engine]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarke-energy.com/gas-type/associated/ |title=Associated Petroleum Gas in Gas Engines |publisher=Clarke Energy |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref> or [[gas turbine|turbine]]s, reinjected for [[secondary recovery]] and used in [[enhanced oil recovery]], converted from [[gas to liquids]] producing [[synthetic fuels]], or used as feedstock for the [[petrochemical industry]].<ref>(Roland 2010 ''cites'' Knizhnikov, A. and N Poussenkova (2009) \u2018Russian Associated Gas Utilization: Problems and Prospects\u2019, Annual Project Report Environment and Energy: International Context Issue 1. Moscow: World Wildlife Fund and Institute of World Economy and International Relations of the Russian Academy of Sciences</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n{{See also|Natural-gas processing}}\nAPG is primarily a mixture of [[hydrocarbon]] molecules that are classified as [[alkanes]].  The following table lists typical percentages of the major alkanes in APG, and includes the typical levels of nitrogen and carbon dioxide.  Water ([[wet gas]]) and [[hydrogen sulfide]] ([[sour gas]]) contaminate APG at more varied levels.  [[Helium]] is present in significant amounts in some cases, and is a relatively valuable by-product.  APG is processed to separate out most other components before the methane-rich gas is sold into natural-gas distribution networks.    \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Component !! Chemical formula !! Volume fraction (%) !! Weight fraction (%)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manbw.ru/analitycs/png.html |script-title=ru:\u041f\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043d\u0435\u0444\u0442\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0433\u0430\u0437: \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u043f\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0431\u044b \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u2013 \u0443\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u041f\u041d\u0413 |trans-title=Associated Petroleum Gas (APG): Basic Methods of Processing and Utilization |language=Russian |publisher=New Generation|date=2013-05-05 }}</ref><!-- These numbers are approximate averages calculated from the associated reference. -->\n|-\n| [[Methane]] || {{chem|CH|4}} ||81|| 60\n|-\n| [[Ethane]] || {{chem|C|2|H|6}} || 5.5 || 7.7\n|-\n| [[Propane]] || {{chem|C|3|H|8}} || 6.6 || 13.5\n|-\n| [[Butane]] || {{chem|C|4|H|10}} || 4.0 || 10.8\n|-\n| [[Pentane]] || {{chem|C|5|H|12}} || 1.4 || 4.8\n|-\n| [[Nitrogen]] || {{chem|N|2}} || 1.0 || 1.3\n|-\n| [[Carbon dioxide]] || {{CO2}} || 0.17 || 0.33\n|}\n\n==Uses==\n{{Main article|Natural gas#Uses}}\nLike crude oil, APG is both a [[primary energy resource]] and a [[primary commodity]] that enables much of the modern [[world economy]].  Statistics from the [[International Energy Agency]] show that the natural-gas supplies steadily increased during 1990-2017 to meet the demands of expanding global [[population growth|population]] and [[consumerism]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.iea.org/data-and-statistics |title=Global Data and Statistics |publisher=[[International Energy Agency]] |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>  APG is nevertheless a finite [[fossil fuel|fossil resource]], and the crossing of [[planetary boundaries]] could impose earlier limits on its value and usefulness.<ref>{{Citation |author=Linnenluecke, Martina K. |author2=Birt, Jac |author3=Lyon John |author4=Sidhu, Baljit K. |title=Planetary boundaries: implications for asset impairment |journal=Accounting and Finance |volume=55 |issue=4 |pages=911\u2013929 |year=2015 |doi=10.1111/acfi.12173 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nFollowing extraction, petroleum companies prefer to transport both crude oil and APG to their respective refiners for processing and distribution to consumers.  Most modern wells are planned to include gas [[pipeline transport]], but some oil wells are drilled only to get the more lucrative oil, in which case the options are to locally use, process, or dispose of the APG.    A traditional local use is to re-inject the gas for storage, and to re-pressurize the well to extend the oil production lifetime.  On-site processing with various mobile systems also exist for producing [[natural gas liquids]] (NGL), [[compressed natural gas]] (CNG), [[liquified natural gas]] (LNG), and [[gas to liquids]] (GTL) fuels that can be transported by truck or ship.  Electricity generation from on-site [[microturbine]]s and [[engine-generator|engines]] is also compatible with minimally processed APG.<ref>{{cite web \n |title=Natural Gas Flaring and Venting: State and Federal Regulatory Overview, Trends, and Impacts \n |url=https://www.energy.gov/sites/prod/files/2019/08/f65/Natural%20Gas%20Flaring%20and%20Venting%20Report.pdf \n |publisher=U.S. Department of Energy \n |accessdate=2019-12-29\n |date=2019-06-01 \n }}</ref>{{rp|50-54}}       \n\n==Flaring==\n{{Main article|Routine flaring}}\nHistorically APG was, and still may be, a waste product from the petroleum extraction industry. It may be a [[stranded gas reserve]] due to the remote location of the oil field, either at sea or on land.  The gas is then simply [[gas venting|vented]] or, preferably, burnt off in [[gas flare]]s. When this occurs it is referred to as '''flare gas'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glossary.oilfield.slb.com/Display.cfm?Term=flare%20gas |title=Flare gas - Oilfield Glossary |publisher=Schlumberger Limited |accessdate=20 May 2011}}</ref> \n\nAPG flaring is controversial since it is a pollutant, a source of global warming<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.foe.co.uk/resource/media_briefing/gasflaringinnigeria.pdf |title=Gas flaring in Nigeria |agency=Friends of the Earth |location=London |date=October 2004 |accessdate=20 May 2011}}</ref> and a waste of a valuable fuel source. APG is flared in many countries where there are significant power shortages.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7820384.stm |title=Nigeria's gas profits go up in smoke |first=Andrew |last=Walker |agency=BBC News |location=Nigeria |date=13 January 2009 |accessdate=20 May 2011}}</ref> In the [[United Kingdom]], gas may not be flared without written consent from the UK government to prevent unnecessary waste and protect the environment.<ref>{{cite web|title=Atmospheric Emission - Flaring|url=http://www.ukooaenvironmentallegislation.co.uk/contents/topic_files/offshore/Flaring.html|publisher=Oil & Gas UK|accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref>  Russia is the world leader and contributed 30 percent of total global APG flared in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oilandgaseurasia.com/articles/p/97/article/883/ |title=Flaring Up - Companies Pay High Costs to be Green |publisher=Oil&Gas Eurasia |date=26 April 2009 |accessdate=20 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[World Bank]] estimates that over 150 billion cubic metres of natural gas are flared or vented annually. Flared natural gas is worth approximately 30.6 billion dollars and equivalent to 25 percent of the United States' yearly gas consumption or 30 percent of the European Union's annual gas consumption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.worldbank.org/ESORQZPSJ0 |title=World Bank, GGFR Partners Unlock Value of Wasted Gas |publisher=World Bank Group |date=14 December 2009 |accessdate=17 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Coalbed methane]] \u2014 Methane associated with coal deposits\n*[[Landfill gas]] \u2014 Methane associated with municipal landfills\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{fuel gas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Associated Petroleum Gas}}\n[[Category:Fuel gas]]\n[[Category:Natural gas]]\n\n[[sv:Fettgas]]\n", "text_old": "'''Associated petroleum gas''' (APG), or '''associated gas''', is a form of [[natural gas]] which is found with deposits of [[petroleum]], either dissolved in the oil or as a free \"gas cap\" above the oil in the reservoir.<ref>{{cite report |first=Tonje Hulbak |last=R\u00f8land |date=2010 |url=http://www.fni.no/doc&pdf/FNI-R1310.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720032900/http://www.fni.no/doc%26pdf/FNI-R1310.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-20 |title=Associated Petroleum Gas in Russia: Reasons for Non-utilization |work=FNI Report 13/2010 |location=Lysaker |publisher=Fridtjof Nansen Institute |page=53 |access-date=2018-10-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| publisher=The Society of Petroleum Engineers |date=2005 |url=http://www.spe.org/industry/docs/GlossaryPetroleumReserves-ResourcesDefinitions_2005.pdf |title=Glossary of terms used in Petroleum Reserves/Resources Definitions |accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref>  The gas can be utilized in a number of ways after processing: sold and included in the natural-gas distribution networks, used for on-site electricity generation with [[gas engine|engine]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarke-energy.com/gas-type/associated/ |title=Associated Petroleum Gas in Gas Engines |publisher=Clarke Energy |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref> or [[gas turbine|turbine]]s, reinjected for [[secondary recovery]] and used in [[enhanced oil recovery]], converted from [[gas to liquids]] producing [[synthetic fuels]], or used as feedstock for the [[petrochemical industry]].<ref>(Roland 2010 ''cites'' Knizhnikov, A. and N Poussenkova (2009) \u2018Russian Associated Gas Utilization: Problems and Prospects\u2019, Annual Project Report Environment and Energy: International Context Issue 1. Moscow: World Wildlife Fund and Institute of World Economy and International Relations of the Russian Academy of Sciences</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n{{See also|Natural-gas processing}}\nAPG is primarily a mixture of [[hydrocarbon]] molecules that are classified as [[alkanes]].  The following table lists typical percentages of the major alkanes in APG, and includes the typical levels of nitrogen and carbon dioxide.  Water ([[wet gas]]) and [[hydrogen sulfide]] ([[sour gas]]) contaminate APG at more varied levels.  [[Helium]] is present in significant amounts in some cases, and is a relatively valuable by-product.  APG is processed to separate out most other components before the methane-rich gas is sold into natural-gas distribution networks.    \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Component !! Chemical formula !! Volume fraction (%) !! Weight fraction (%)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manbw.ru/analitycs/png.html |script-title=ru:\u041f\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043d\u0435\u0444\u0442\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0433\u0430\u0437: \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u043f\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0431\u044b \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u2013 \u0443\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u041f\u041d\u0413 |trans-title=Associated Petroleum Gas (APG): Basic Methods of Processing and Utilization |language=Russian |publisher=New Generation|date=2013-05-05 }}</ref><!-- These numbers are approximate averages calculated from the associated reference. -->\n|-\n| [[Methane]] || {{chem|CH|4}} ||81|| 60\n|-\n| [[Ethane]] || {{chem|C|2|H|6}} || 5.5 || 7.7\n|-\n| [[Propane]] || {{chem|C|3|H|8}} || 6.6 || 13.5\n|-\n| [[Butane]] || {{chem|C|4|H|10}} || 4.0 || 10.8\n|-\n| [[Pentane]] || {{chem|C|5|H|12}} || 1.4 || 4.8\n|-\n| [[Nitrogen]] || {{chem|N|2}} || 1.0 || 1.3\n|-\n| [[Carbon dioxide]] || {{CO2}} || 0.17 || 0.33\n|}\n\n==Uses==\n{{Main article|Natural gas#Uses}}\nLike crude oil, APG is both a [[primary energy resource]] and a [[primary commodity]] that enables much of the modern [[world economy]].  Statistics from the [[International Energy Agency]] show that the natural-gas supplies steadily increased during 1990-2017 to meet the demands of expanding global [[population growth|population]] and [[consumerism]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.iea.org/data-and-statistics |title=Gobal Data and Statistics |publisher=[[International Energy Agency]] |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>  APG is nevertheless a finite [[fossil fuel|fossil resource]], and the crossing of [[planetary boundaries]] could impose earlier limits on its value and usefulness.<ref>{{Citation |author=Linnenluecke, Martina K. |author2=Birt, Jac |author3=Lyon John |author4=Sidhu, Baljit K. |title=Planetary boundaries: implications for asset impairment |journal=Accounting and Finance |volume=55 |issue=4 |pages=911\u2013929 |year=2015 |doi=10.1111/acfi.12173 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nFollowing extraction, petroleum companies prefer to transport both crude oil and APG to their respective refiners for processing and distribution to consumers.  Most modern wells are planned to include gas [[pipeline transport]], but some oil wells are drilled only to get the more lucrative oil, in which case the options are to locally use, process, or dispose of the APG.    A traditional local use is to re-inject the gas for storage, and to re-pressurize the well to extend the oil production lifetime.  On-site processing with various mobile systems also exist for producing [[natural gas liquids]] (NGL), [[compressed natural gas]] (CNG), [[liquified natural gas]] (LNG), and [[gas to liquids]] (GTL) fuels that can be transported by truck or ship.  Electricity generation from on-site [[microturbine]]s and [[engine-generator|engines]] is also compatible with minimally processed APG.<ref>{{cite web \n |title=Natural Gas Flaring and Venting: State and Federal Regulatory Overview, Trends, and Impacts \n |url=https://www.energy.gov/sites/prod/files/2019/08/f65/Natural%20Gas%20Flaring%20and%20Venting%20Report.pdf \n |publisher=U.S. Department of Energy \n |accessdate=2019-12-29\n |date=2019-06-01 \n }}</ref>{{rp|50-54}}       \n\n==Flaring==\n{{Main article|Routine flaring}}\nHistorically APG was, and still may be, a waste product from the petroleum extraction industry. It may be a [[stranded gas reserve]] due to the remote location of the oil field, either at sea or on land.  The gas is then simply [[gas venting|vented]] or, preferably, burnt off in [[gas flare]]s. When this occurs it is referred to as '''flare gas'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glossary.oilfield.slb.com/Display.cfm?Term=flare%20gas |title=Flare gas - Oilfield Glossary |publisher=Schlumberger Limited |accessdate=20 May 2011}}</ref> \n\nAPG flaring is controversial since it is a pollutant, a source of global warming<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.foe.co.uk/resource/media_briefing/gasflaringinnigeria.pdf |title=Gas flaring in Nigeria |agency=Friends of the Earth |location=London |date=October 2004 |accessdate=20 May 2011}}</ref> and a waste of a valuable fuel source. APG is flared in many countries where there are significant power shortages.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7820384.stm |title=Nigeria's gas profits go up in smoke |first=Andrew |last=Walker |agency=BBC News |location=Nigeria |date=13 January 2009 |accessdate=20 May 2011}}</ref> In the [[United Kingdom]], gas may not be flared without written consent from the UK government to prevent unnecessary waste and protect the environment.<ref>{{cite web|title=Atmospheric Emission - Flaring|url=http://www.ukooaenvironmentallegislation.co.uk/contents/topic_files/offshore/Flaring.html|publisher=Oil & Gas UK|accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref>  Russia is the world leader and contributed 30 percent of total global APG flared in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oilandgaseurasia.com/articles/p/97/article/883/ |title=Flaring Up - Companies Pay High Costs to be Green |publisher=Oil&Gas Eurasia |date=26 April 2009 |accessdate=20 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[World Bank]] estimates that over 150 billion cubic metres of natural gas are flared or vented annually. Flared natural gas is worth approximately 30.6 billion dollars and equivalent to 25 percent of the United States' yearly gas consumption or 30 percent of the European Union's annual gas consumption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go.worldbank.org/ESORQZPSJ0 |title=World Bank, GGFR Partners Unlock Value of Wasted Gas |publisher=World Bank Group |date=14 December 2009 |accessdate=17 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Coalbed methane]] \u2014 Methane associated with coal deposits\n*[[Landfill gas]] \u2014 Methane associated with municipal landfills\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{fuel gas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Associated Petroleum Gas}}\n[[Category:Fuel gas]]\n[[Category:Natural gas]]\n\n[[sv:Fettgas]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Associated_petroleum_gas"}
{"title_page": "Sports in New Jersey", "text_new": "[[File:New Meadowlands Stadium Mezz Corner.jpg|thumb|[[MetLife Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford]], Bergen County, home to the NFL's New York Giants and New York Jets and the most expensive stadium ever built.<ref name=\"Esteban\">{{cite web|url=http://www.totalprosports.com/2011/10/27/11-most-expensive-stadiums-in-the-world/|title=11 Most Expensive Stadiums In The World|publisher=Total Pro Sports|author=Esteban|date=October 27, 2011|accessdate=September 2, 2012}}</ref>]]\n[[New Jersey]] currently has six teams from [[major professional sports league]]s playing in the state, with only one team identifying themselves as being from the state. The other remaining teams identify themselves as being from the [[New York metropolitan area]] with the exception of the [[National Women's Soccer League]] team that has chosen a team name that does not identify with New Jersey or New York.\n==Professional sports==\n[[File:Pudcentnewarkjeh.JPG|thumb|The [[Prudential Center]] in Newark, home of the NHL's New Jersey Devils.]]\n[[File:Le Red Bull Arena.jpg|thumb|[[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]] in [[Harrison, New Jersey|Harrison]], [[Hudson County, New Jersey|Hudson County]], home of the MLS's New York Red Bulls.]]\nThe [[National Hockey League]]'s [[New Jersey Devils]], based in [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]] at the [[Prudential Center]], is the only major league franchise to bear the state's name. Founded in 1974 in [[Kansas City, Missouri]] as the [[Kansas City Scouts]], the team played in [[Denver, Colorado]] as the [[Colorado Rockies (NHL)|Colorado Rockies]] from 1976 until the spring of 1982 when naval architect, businessman, and [[Jersey City]] native [[John J. McMullen]] purchased and relocated the franchise to [[Brendan Byrne Arena]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford's]] [[Meadowlands Sports Complex]] under its current identity. While the organization was largely a failure on the ice in Kansas City, Denver, and its first years in New Jersey, the Devils would ultimately begin their rise to prominence in the late 1980s and early 1990s under the tenure of Hall of Fame president and general manager [[Lou Lamoriello]], winning the [[Stanley Cup]] in 1995, 2000, and 2003, and act as an annual fixture in the Stanley Cup playoffs for the majority of two decades. The organization is the youngest out of all nine \"Big Four\" major league teams within the New York Metropolitan Area and media market dominated in terms of ice hockey by the [[New York Rangers]] and [[New York Islanders|Islanders]] prior to the Devils' arrival, but has ultimately been successful in establishing a visible and dedicated following throughout the northern and central portions of the state. In 2018, one of the Devils' fiercest rivals, the [[Philadelphia Flyers]], renovated and expanded their training facility, The Virtua Center Flyers Skate Zone, in [[Voorhees Township, New Jersey|Voorhees Township]] in the southern portion of the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/news/2018/02/22/virtua-flyers-training-facility-voorhees-remodeled.html|title=Check out the Flyers renovated & expanded South Jersey training facility|publisher=Philadelphia Business Journal|date=February 22, 2018|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe New York Metropolitan Area's two [[National Football League]] teams, the [[New York Giants]] and the [[New York Jets]], both play at [[MetLife Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford's]]\n[[Meadowlands Sports Complex]].<ref>[http://www.newmeadowlandsstadium.com/ New Meadowlands Stadium official website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009075832/http://www.newmeadowlandsstadium.com/ |date=2014-10-09 }} New Meadowlands Stadium Corporation. Retrieved June 14, 2010.</ref> At completion, with a construction cost of approximately $1.6 billion,<ref name=\"Belson\">{{cite news|first=Ken|last=Belson|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/09/sports/football/09stadium.html|newspaper=The New York Times|title=New Stadium, a Football Palace, Opens Saturday With Lacrosse|date=April 8, 2010|accessdate=March 21, 2011}}</ref> the venue is the most expensive stadium ever built.<ref name=\"Esteban\"/> On February 2, 2014, MetLife Stadium was the host for [[Super Bowl XLVIII]]. In 2020, the [[New York Guardians]] of the [[XFL (2020)|XFL]] began playing at Metlife Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elitesportsny.com/2020/02/06/esny-exclusive-new-york-guardians-take-over-metlife-stadium/|title=ESNY Exclusive: New York Guardians take over MetLife Stadium|website=elitesportsny.com|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[New York Red Bulls]] of [[Major League Soccer]] play in [[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]], a soccer-specific stadium located in [[Harrison, New Jersey|Harrison]] immediately across the [[Passaic River]] from downtown [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]]. On July 27, 2011, Red Bull Arena hosted the [[2011 MLS All-Star Game]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester United's 4-0 Romp Over MLS All-Stars More Proof U.S. Pro Soccer Not Up to Snuff|first=Filip|last=Bondy|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more_sports/2011/07/28/2011-07-28_results_show_mls_lacks_solid_footing.html|newspaper=Daily News|location=New York|date=July 28, 2011|accessdate=December 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1977 to 2012, New Jersey had a [[National Basketball Association]] team, the [[New Jersey Nets]]. Also, [[WNBA]]'s [[New York Liberty]] played in New Jersey from 2011 to 2013. In 2016, the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] of the NBA opened their new headquarters and training facility, the Philadelphia 76ers Training Complex, in [[Camden, New Jersey|Camden]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Seltzer|first1=Brian|title=On the Beat: New Training Complex Brings Modern Feel, Promise|url=http://www.nba.com/sixers/beat-new-training-complex-brings-modern-feel-promise|website=NBA.com|accessdate=January 31, 2018|date=September 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Meadowlands Sports Complex is also home to the [[Meadowlands Racetrack]], one of two major [[harness racing]] tracks in the state. The Meadowlands Racetrack along with [[Freehold Raceway]] in Freehold are two of the major harness racing tracks in North America. [[Monmouth Park Racetrack]] in Oceanport is also a popular spot for [[thoroughbred racing]] in New Jersey and the northeast. It hosted the [[Breeders' Cup]] in 2007, and its turf course was renovated in preparation.\n\n===Major league sports===\n====New Jersey teams====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Club !! Sport !! League !! Stadium (capacity) !! Established !! Titles\n|-\n| '''[[New Jersey Devils]]''' || rowspan=\"2\" | Ice hockey || [[National Hockey League]] || [[Prudential Center]] (16,514) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1974 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3\n|-\n| '''[[Metropolitan Riveters]]''' ||[[National Women's Hockey League]] || \tProSkate Ice Arena || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2015 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1\n|-\n| '''[[Sky Blue FC]]''' || Soccer || [[National Women's Soccer League]] || [[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]] (25,000) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2007 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1\n|}\n\n====New York Metropolitan teams that play in New Jersey====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Club !! Sport !! League !! Stadium (capacity) !! Established !! Titles\n|-\n| '''[[New York Jets]]''' || rowspan=\"2\" | Football || rowspan=\"2\" | [[National Football League]] || rowspan=\"2\" | [[MetLife Stadium]] (82,500) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1959 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1\n|-\n| '''[[New York Giants]]'''  || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1925 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8\n|-\n| '''[[New York Red Bulls]]''' || Soccer || [[Major League Soccer]] || [[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]] (25,000) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1994 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|}\n\n===Semi-pro and minor league sports===\n====New Jersey teams====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Club !! Sport !! League !! Stadium (capacity) !! Established !! Titles\n|-\n| '''[[Trenton Thunder]]''' || rowspan=\"5\" | Baseball || [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] ([[Minor League Baseball|MiLB]] -[[Double-A (baseball)|AA]]) || [[Arm & Hammer Park]] (6,150) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1980 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3\n|-\n| '''[[Lakewood BlueClaws]]''' || [[South Atlantic League]] ([[Minor League Baseball|MiLB]]-[[Single-A (baseball)|A]]) || [[FirstEnergy Park]] (8,000) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1987 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3\n|-\n| '''[[Somerset Patriots]]''' ||[[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]] || [[TD Bank Ballpark]] (6,100) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1997 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6\n|-\n| '''[[New Jersey Jackals]]''' || rowspan=\"2\" |[[Frontier League]]||[[Yogi Berra Stadium]] (5,000) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1998 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5\n|-\n| '''[[Sussex County Miners]]''' ||[[Skylands Stadium]] (4,200) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2015 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1\n|-\n| '''[[Jersey Express]]''' || Basketball || [[American Basketball Association (2000\u2013present)|American Basketball Association]] || Joseph Battin School No.4 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2005 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[[Jersey Flight]]''' || [[Indoor American football|Indoor football]] || [[National Arena League]] || [[CURE Insurance Arena]] (10,000) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2018 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[[Ocean City Nor'easters]]''' || rowspan=\"10\" |  Soccer || rowspan=\"2\" | [[USL League Two]] || [[Carey Stadium]] ||  style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1996 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3\n|-\n| '''[[Cedar Stars Rush]]''' || [[Fairleigh Dickinson University]] ||  style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2018 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[[FC Motown]]''' || rowspan=\"4\" | [[National Premier Soccer League]] || [[Drew University | Ranger Stadium]] ||  style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2012 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[[New Jersey Copa FC]]''' || [[St. John Vianney High School]] ||  style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2015 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[[Atlantic City FC]]''' || [[Egg Harbor Township High School]] ||  style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2018 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[[FC Monmouth]]''' || Count Basie Park ||  style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2018 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[[New Jersey Teamsters FC]]''' ||  [[National Independent Soccer Association]] || Don Ahern Veterans Memorial Stadium ||  style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2017 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[[New Jersey Copa FC]]''' || [[United Women's Soccer]] || [[Mercer County Community College]] ||  style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2015 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[https://www.wpslsoccer.com/page/show/5567521-psa-wildcats?subseason=670624  PSA Wildcats]''' || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Women's Premier Soccer League]] || [[Woodbridge High School (New Jersey) | Woodbridge High School]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1996 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[https://www.wpslsoccer.com/page/show/5567522-nj-wizards-sc?subseason=670624 NJ Wizards SC]''' || [[Cedar Grove High School (New Jersey) | Cedar Grove High School]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | - || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|}\n\n====New York Metropolitan minor league teams that play in New Jersey====\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Club !! Sport !! League !! Stadium (capacity) !! Established !! Titles\n|-\n| '''[[New York Red Bulls II]]''' || Soccer || [[USL Championship]] || [[MSU Soccer Park at Pittser Field]] (5,000) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2015 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1\n|}\n\n==College sports==\n\n===Major schools===\nNew Jerseyans' collegiate allegiances are predominantly split among the three major [[NCAA Division I]] programs in the state \u2013 the [[Rutgers University\u2013New Brunswick|Rutgers University]] (New Jersey's flagship state university) [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights|Scarlet Knights]], members of the [[Big Ten Conference]]; the [[Seton Hall University]] (the state's largest [[Catholic Church in the United States|Catholic]] university) [[Seton Hall Pirates|Pirates]], members of the [[Big East Conference]]; and the [[Princeton University]] (the state's [[Ivy League]] university) [[Princeton Tigers|Tigers]].\n\nRutgers and Princeton athletics share an intense rivalry \u2013 stemming from the [[1869 college football season|first intercollegiate football game]] in 1869 \u2013 though the two schools have not met on the football field since 1980. They continue to play each other annually in all other sports offered by the two universities.\n\nRutgers, which fields 24 teams in various sports, is nationally known for its excellent football and women's basketball programs, owning a 6-4 all-time [[bowl game|bowl]] record and appearing in a [[2007 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|National Final]] in 2007, respectively. In 2008 and 2009, Rutgers expanded their football home [[HighPoint.com Stadium]] on the [[Busch Campus of Rutgers University|Busch Campus]], and the basketball teams play at [[Louis Brown Athletic Center]] on [[Livingston Campus (Rutgers University)|Livingston Campus]]. Both venues and campuses are located in [[Piscataway Township, New Jersey|Piscataway]], immediately across the [[Raritan River]] from [[New Brunswick, New Jersey|New Brunswick]]. The university also fields rising men's basketball and baseball programs. Rutgers' fan base is mostly derived from the western parts of the state and [[Middlesex County, New Jersey|Middlesex County]], not to mention its alumni base, which is the largest in the state.\n\nRutgers' satellite campuses in Camden and Newark each field their own athletic programs. The [[Rutgers\u2013Camden]] athletic teams are called the [[Rutgers\u2013Camden Scarlet Raptors|Scarlet Raptors]]. The [[Rutgers\u2013Newark]] athletic teams are called the [[Rutgers\u2013Newark Scarlet Raiders|Scarlet Raiders]]. The Scarlet Raiders and the Scarlet Raptors both compete within NCAA [[Division III (NCAA)|Division III]].\n\nSeton Hall, unlike Rutgers and Princeton, does not field a football team. Its men's basketball team, however, is one of the Big East's storied programs, New Jersey's most successful representative in the [[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament]] by number of wins, the state's only men's basketball program to reach a modern [[1989 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|National Final]], and plays its home games at [[Prudential Center]] in downtown [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]] approximately four miles from the university's [[South Orange, New Jersey|South Orange]] campus. The Pirates, while lacking as large an alumni base as the state university, have a large well of support in the predominantly Roman Catholic areas of the northern part of the state and the [[Jersey Shore]]. The annual inter-conference rivalry game between Seton Hall and Rutgers which alternates between Newark and Piscataway, the Garden State Hardwood Classic, has been renewed through 2026.<ref>https://www.app.com/story/sports/college/2018/04/30/rutgers-seton-hall-basketball-garden-state-hardwood-classic/563768002/</ref>\n\n===Other schools===\nThe state's other Division I schools include the [[Monmouth Hawks|Monmouth University Hawks]] (West Long Branch), the [[NJIT Mens Soccer|New Jersey Institute of Technology (NJIT) Highlanders]] (Newark), the [[Rider University#Athletics|Rider University Broncs]] (Lawrenceville), and the [[Saint Peter's College, New Jersey#Athletics|Saint Peter's University Peacocks and Peahens]] (Jersey City).\n\n[[Fairleigh Dickinson Knights|Fairleigh Dickinson University]] competes in both Division I and Division III. It has two campuses, each with its own sports teams. The teams at the Metropolitan Campus are known as the FDU Knights, and compete in the [[Northeast Conference]] and NCAA Division I. The College at Florham (FDU-Florham) teams are known as the FDU-Florham Devils and compete in the [[Middle Atlantic Conferences#Freedom Conference|Middle Atlantic Conferences' Freedom Conference]] and NCAA Division III.\n\nAmong the various Division III schools in the state, the [[Stevens Tech Ducks football|Stevens Institute of Technology]] Ducks have fielded the longest continuously running collegiate men's lacrosse program in the country. 2009 marked the 125th season.\n\n==High school sports==\nNew Jersey high schools are divided into divisions under the [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]].(NJSIAA) <ref>[http://www.njsiaa.org/ NJSIAA<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>'<ref>[http://www.ihigh.com/NJ/ New Jersey High School News and Sports] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418224118/http://www.ihigh.com/NJ/ |date=2009-04-18 }}. iHigh.com, Inc \u2013 The High School Internet Network. Retrieved January 26, 2011.</ref> Founded in 1918, the NJSIAA currently represents 22,000 schools, 330,000 coaches, and almost 4.5 million athletes. Sports are divided between 3 seasons (fall, winter, and spring).\n\n==Academies and clubs==\nNew Jersey also features a collection of sports leagues, clubs, and academies for athletic training. Like many suburban communities, most New Jersey towns have individual leagues for America's most popular sports - baseball, softball, football, cheerleading, basketball, soccer, etc.<ref>[http://jerseyclubsports.com/ Jersey Club Sports - Have Fun. Play Sports. Be Social!<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Stadiums and arenas==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Venue !! City !! Capacity !! Type !! Tenants !! Opened\n|-\n| [[SHI Stadium]] || [[Piscataway, New Jersey|Piscataway]] || 52,454 || [[Stadium]] || [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights]] || 1994\n|- \n| [[Jadwin Gymnasium]] || [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]] || 6,854 || [[Arena]] || [[Princeton Tigers]] || 1969\n|-\n| [[Louis Brown Athletic Center]] || Piscataway || 8,000 || Arena || Rutgers Scarlet Knights || 1977\n|-\n| [[MetLife Stadium]] || [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford]] || 82,500 || Stadium || [[New York Giants]], [[New York Jets]], [[New York Guardians]] || 2010\n|-\n| [[Princeton University Stadium]] || Princeton || 27,800 || Stadium || Princeton Tigers || 1998\n|-\n| [[Prudential Center]] || [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]] || 18,711 || Arena || [[New Jersey Devils]], [[Seton Hall Pirates]] || 2007\n|-\n| [[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]] || [[Harrison, New Jersey|Harrison]] || 25,189 || Stadium || [[New York Red Bulls]], [[Sky Blue FC]] || 2010\n|-\n|[[FirstEnergy Park|FirstEnergy Park]] ||[[Lakewood BlueClaws|Lakewood]] || 8,000 || Stadium || [[Lakewood BlueClaws]] || 2001\n|}\n\n==Other notable sports venues==\n* [[Old Bridge Township Raceway Park]]\n* [[Trenton Speedway]]\n* [[Atlantic City Race Course]]\n* [[Freehold Raceway]]\n* [[Garden State Park Racetrack]]\n* [[Monmouth Park Racetrack]]\n* [[Meadowlands Sports Complex]]\n** [[Meadowlands Arena]]\n** [[Meadowlands Racetrack]]\n** [[Meadowlands Grand Prix]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of college athletic programs in New Jersey]]\n* [[Sports Hall of Fame of New Jersey]]\n* [[New Jersey Sports Writers Association Hall of Fame]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n\n{{New Jersey Sports}}\n{{Sports in the United States}}\n{{New Jersey}}\n\n[[Category:Sports in New Jersey| ]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:New Meadowlands Stadium Mezz Corner.jpg|thumb|[[MetLife Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford]], Bergen County, home to the NFL's New York Giants and New York Jets and the most expensive stadium ever built.<ref name=\"Esteban\">{{cite web|url=http://www.totalprosports.com/2011/10/27/11-most-expensive-stadiums-in-the-world/|title=11 Most Expensive Stadiums In The World|publisher=Total Pro Sports|author=Esteban|date=October 27, 2011|accessdate=September 2, 2012}}</ref>]]\n[[New Jersey]] currently has six teams from [[major professional sports league]]s playing in the state, with only one team identifies themselves as being from the state. The other remaining teams identify themselves as being from the [[New York metropolitan area]] with the exception of the [[National Women's Soccer League]] team that has chosen a team name that does not identify with New Jersey or New York.\n==Professional sports==\n[[File:Pudcentnewarkjeh.JPG|thumb|The [[Prudential Center]] in Newark, home of the NHL's New Jersey Devils.]]\n[[File:Le Red Bull Arena.jpg|thumb|[[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]] in [[Harrison, New Jersey|Harrison]], [[Hudson County, New Jersey|Hudson County]], home of the MLS's New York Red Bulls.]]\nThe [[National Hockey League]]'s [[New Jersey Devils]], based in [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]] at the [[Prudential Center]], is the only major league franchise to bear the state's name. Founded in 1974 in [[Kansas City, Missouri]] as the [[Kansas City Scouts]], the team played in [[Denver, Colorado]] as the [[Colorado Rockies (NHL)|Colorado Rockies]] from 1976 until the spring of 1982 when naval architect, businessman, and [[Jersey City]] native [[John J. McMullen]] purchased and relocated the franchise to [[Brendan Byrne Arena]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford's]] [[Meadowlands Sports Complex]] under its current identity. While the organization was largely a failure on the ice in Kansas City, Denver, and its first years in New Jersey, the Devils would ultimately begin their rise to prominence in the late 1980s and early 1990s under the tenure of Hall of Fame president and general manager [[Lou Lamoriello]], winning the [[Stanley Cup]] in 1995, 2000, and 2003, and act as an annual fixture in the Stanley Cup playoffs for the majority of two decades. The organization is the youngest out of all nine \"Big Four\" major league teams within the New York Metropolitan Area and media market dominated in terms of ice hockey by the [[New York Rangers]] and [[New York Islanders|Islanders]] prior to the Devils' arrival, but has ultimately been successful in establishing a visible and dedicated following throughout the northern and central portions of the state. In 2018, one of the Devils' fiercest rivals, the [[Philadelphia Flyers]], renovated and expanded their training facility, The Virtua Center Flyers Skate Zone, in [[Voorhees Township, New Jersey|Voorhees Township]] in the southern portion of the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/news/2018/02/22/virtua-flyers-training-facility-voorhees-remodeled.html|title=Check out the Flyers renovated & expanded South Jersey training facility|publisher=Philadelphia Business Journal|date=February 22, 2018|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe New York Metropolitan Area's two [[National Football League]] teams, the [[New York Giants]] and the [[New York Jets]], both play at [[MetLife Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford's]]\n[[Meadowlands Sports Complex]].<ref>[http://www.newmeadowlandsstadium.com/ New Meadowlands Stadium official website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009075832/http://www.newmeadowlandsstadium.com/ |date=2014-10-09 }} New Meadowlands Stadium Corporation. Retrieved June 14, 2010.</ref> At completion, with a construction cost of approximately $1.6 billion,<ref name=\"Belson\">{{cite news|first=Ken|last=Belson|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/09/sports/football/09stadium.html|newspaper=The New York Times|title=New Stadium, a Football Palace, Opens Saturday With Lacrosse|date=April 8, 2010|accessdate=March 21, 2011}}</ref> the venue is the most expensive stadium ever built.<ref name=\"Esteban\"/> On February 2, 2014, MetLife Stadium was the host for [[Super Bowl XLVIII]]. In 2020, the [[New York Guardians]] of the [[XFL (2020)|XFL]] began playing at Metlife Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elitesportsny.com/2020/02/06/esny-exclusive-new-york-guardians-take-over-metlife-stadium/|title=ESNY Exclusive: New York Guardians take over MetLife Stadium|website=elitesportsny.com|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[New York Red Bulls]] of [[Major League Soccer]] play in [[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]], a soccer-specific stadium located in [[Harrison, New Jersey|Harrison]] immediately across the [[Passaic River]] from downtown [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]]. On July 27, 2011, Red Bull Arena hosted the [[2011 MLS All-Star Game]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester United's 4-0 Romp Over MLS All-Stars More Proof U.S. Pro Soccer Not Up to Snuff|first=Filip|last=Bondy|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more_sports/2011/07/28/2011-07-28_results_show_mls_lacks_solid_footing.html|newspaper=Daily News|location=New York|date=July 28, 2011|accessdate=December 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1977 to 2012, New Jersey had a [[National Basketball Association]] team, the [[New Jersey Nets]]. Also, [[WNBA]]'s [[New York Liberty]] played in New Jersey from 2011 to 2013. In 2016, the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] of the NBA opened their new headquarters and training facility, the Philadelphia 76ers Training Complex, in [[Camden, New Jersey|Camden]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Seltzer|first1=Brian|title=On the Beat: New Training Complex Brings Modern Feel, Promise|url=http://www.nba.com/sixers/beat-new-training-complex-brings-modern-feel-promise|website=NBA.com|accessdate=January 31, 2018|date=September 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Meadowlands Sports Complex is also home to the [[Meadowlands Racetrack]], one of two major [[harness racing]] tracks in the state. The Meadowlands Racetrack along with [[Freehold Raceway]] in Freehold are two of the major harness racing tracks in North America. [[Monmouth Park Racetrack]] in Oceanport is also a popular spot for [[thoroughbred racing]] in New Jersey and the northeast. It hosted the [[Breeders' Cup]] in 2007, and its turf course was renovated in preparation.\n\n===Major league sports===\n====New Jersey teams====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Club !! Sport !! League !! Stadium (capacity) !! Established !! Titles\n|-\n| '''[[New Jersey Devils]]''' || rowspan=\"2\" | Ice hockey || [[National Hockey League]] || [[Prudential Center]] (16,514) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1974 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3\n|-\n| '''[[Metropolitan Riveters]]''' ||[[National Women's Hockey League]] || \tProSkate Ice Arena || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2015 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1\n|-\n| '''[[Sky Blue FC]]''' || Soccer || [[National Women's Soccer League]] || [[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]] (25,000) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2007 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1\n|}\n\n====New York Metropolitan teams that play in New Jersey====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Club !! Sport !! League !! Stadium (capacity) !! Established !! Titles\n|-\n| '''[[New York Jets]]''' || rowspan=\"2\" | Football || rowspan=\"2\" | [[National Football League]] || rowspan=\"2\" | [[MetLife Stadium]] (82,500) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1959 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1\n|-\n| '''[[New York Giants]]'''  || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1925 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8\n|-\n| '''[[New York Red Bulls]]''' || Soccer || [[Major League Soccer]] || [[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]] (25,000) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1994 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|}\n\n===Semi-pro and minor league sports===\n====New Jersey teams====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Club !! Sport !! League !! Stadium (capacity) !! Established !! Titles\n|-\n| '''[[Trenton Thunder]]''' || rowspan=\"5\" | Baseball || [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] ([[Minor League Baseball|MiLB]] -[[Double-A (baseball)|AA]]) || [[Arm & Hammer Park]] (6,150) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1980 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3\n|-\n| '''[[Lakewood BlueClaws]]''' || [[South Atlantic League]] ([[Minor League Baseball|MiLB]]-[[Single-A (baseball)|A]]) || [[FirstEnergy Park]] (8,000) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1987 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3\n|-\n| '''[[Somerset Patriots]]''' ||[[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]] || [[TD Bank Ballpark]] (6,100) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1997 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6\n|-\n| '''[[New Jersey Jackals]]''' || rowspan=\"2\" |[[Frontier League]]||[[Yogi Berra Stadium]] (5,000) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1998 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5\n|-\n| '''[[Sussex County Miners]]''' ||[[Skylands Stadium]] (4,200) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2015 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1\n|-\n| '''[[Jersey Express]]''' || Basketball || [[American Basketball Association (2000\u2013present)|American Basketball Association]] || Joseph Battin School No.4 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2005 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[[Jersey Flight]]''' || [[Indoor American football|Indoor football]] || [[National Arena League]] || [[CURE Insurance Arena]] (10,000) || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2018 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[[Ocean City Nor'easters]]''' || rowspan=\"10\" |  Soccer || rowspan=\"2\" | [[USL League Two]] || [[Carey Stadium]] ||  style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1996 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3\n|-\n| '''[[Cedar Stars Rush]]''' || [[Fairleigh Dickinson University]] ||  style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2018 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[[FC Motown]]''' || rowspan=\"4\" | [[National Premier Soccer League]] || [[Drew University | Ranger Stadium]] ||  style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2012 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 0\n|-\n| '''[[New Jersey Copa FC]]''' || [[St. John Vianney High School]] ||  style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2015 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 